Public health officials will mount a massive defense to contain potential flare-ups — sparks of individual cases that could reignite another outbreak.
But already many public health experts are thinking beyond May or even June, when California’s outbreak presumably will be waning or possibly gone altogether.
Meanwhile, public health officials must be able to quickly identify and isolate new infections to prevent them from spreading.
On Friday, public health officials in Contra Costa County announced that 27 patients in a 47-bed facility in Orinda had tested positive for the virus.
Some public health experts have suggested that counties start hiring out-of-work people now and train them to do contact tracing.